        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2126066220" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15365526593857471127">It took me a little longer than I expected to read this rather fascinating book as it slowed down to a crawl toward the end. Most history readers are familiar with the dissection of the Middle East (as well as parts of Europe) as a result of the infamous Versailles Treaty. At the beginning of the war, the Ottoman Empire, caught in the middle of this disruption, was already shaky at best and its own people couldn&apos;t decide which side they should take. This was a &quot;empire&quot; that spoke many languages,</span>
  <span id="freeText15365526593857471127" style="display:none">It took me a little longer than I expected to read this rather fascinating book as it slowed down to a crawl toward the end. Most history readers are familiar with the dissection of the Middle East (as well as parts of Europe) as a result of the infamous Versailles Treaty. At the beginning of the war, the Ottoman Empire, caught in the middle of this disruption, was already shaky at best and its own people couldn't decide which side they should take. This was a "empire" that spoke many languages, had many religions, and no common cultural base, so it is not surprising that it was caught in a whirlwind of espionage, broken treaties, and inept leadership.<br /><br />Moving toward more modern times, the effects of the above stated differences muddied the waters and prevented the creation of a cohesive agreement among the countries involved. The Ottoman Empire disappeared and problems arose that still resonate today. An interesting read which also looks beneath some of the myths of that troubled time. Recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15365526593857471127" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


