<div id="review_3386094709" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3386094709" />
    <a title="Samantha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8287392-samantha"><img alt="Samantha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600575930p2/8287392.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3386094709?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Samantha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Samantha" href="/user/show/8287392-samantha">Samantha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8287392-samantha?shelf=middle-eastern-history">middle-eastern-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3386094709" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9991816213369928851">This book provides a comprehensive history of the fall of the Ottoman Empire and the carving up of the empire post WW1 culminating in what the author coins the Middle East Settlement of 1922. The book is divided into twelve well constructed and chronological parts. For WW1 history buffs there may not be much you don&apos;t already know here except a very detailed summary of the ins-and-outs/plotting/miscalculations of the English Egyptian, Indian and Middle East bureaus during this time - how strateg</span>
  <span id="freeText9991816213369928851" style="display:none">This book provides a comprehensive history of the fall of the Ottoman Empire and the carving up of the empire post WW1 culminating in what the author coins the Middle East Settlement of 1922. The book is divided into twelve well constructed and chronological parts. For WW1 history buffs there may not be much you don't already know here except a very detailed summary of the ins-and-outs/plotting/miscalculations of the English Egyptian, Indian and Middle East bureaus during this time - how strategy was directed/misdirected by competing forces and the ultimate inevitable abandonment of the original expansion of empire plan due to economic, nationalist, domestic and geopolitical forces post WW1. Kitchener, Asquith and Churchill feature predominantly as to be expected. For a non-WW1 buff the book gave me a great perspective on some of the eastern front operations, particularly in Central Asia.<br /><br />This was not an easy read but very worth while as I don't believe it is possible to have perspective on the current Middle East as we know it today without understanding it's creation. The author's afterward to the 2009 edition summarises this importance well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9991816213369928851" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


